description: Learned borrowing from Latin rēticulātus (“reticulated, net-like”).

adjectives.description: reticulate (comparative more reticulate, superlative most reticulate)

examples: The fingers have a pseudosclerodermatous appearance with scleroatrophy, often with contractures and sometimes with reticulate erythema on the dorsal surface.

verbs.description: reticulate (third-person singular simple present reticulates, present participle reticulating, simple past and past participle reticulated)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To distribute or move via a network.
(transitive) To divide into or form a network.
